WEBVTT

00:19.260 --> 00:22.320
VIII. The Village.

00:23.340 --> 00:30.140
After hoeing, or perhaps reading and writing, in the forenoon I usually bathed again in

00:30.140 --> 00:37.020
the pond, swimming across one of its coves for a stint, and washed the dust of labor

00:37.020 --> 00:42.800
from my person, or smoothed out the last wrinkle which study had made, and for the afternoon

00:42.800 --> 00:49.360
was absolutely free. Every day or two I strolled to the village to hear some of the gossip

00:49.360 --> 00:54.680
which is incessantly going on there, circulating either from mouth to mouth or from newspaper

00:54.680 --> 01:02.000
to newspaper, and which, taken in homeopathic doses, was really as refreshing in its way

01:02.000 --> 01:07.280
as the rustle of leaves and the peeping of frogs. As I walked in the woods to see the

01:07.280 --> 01:13.120
birds and squirrels, so I walked in the village to see the men and boys. Instead of the wind

01:13.120 --> 01:19.160
among the pines I heard the carts rattle. In one direction from my house there was a

01:19.160 --> 01:25.820
colony of muskrats, in the river meadows, under the grove of elms and buttonwoods. In

01:25.820 --> 01:32.380
the other horizon was a village of busy men, as curious to me as if they had been prairie

01:32.380 --> 01:38.980
dogs, each sitting at the mouth of its burrow, or running over to a neighbor's to gossip.

01:39.880 --> 01:47.020
I went there frequently to observe their habits. The village appeared to me a great newsroom,

01:47.760 --> 01:55.320
and, on one side, to support it, as once at Redding & Company's on State Street they kept

01:55.320 --> 02:01.960
nuts and raisins, or salt and meal and other groceries. Some have such a vast appetite

02:01.960 --> 02:09.100
for the former commodity, that is, the news, and such sound digestive organs, that they

02:09.100 --> 02:14.100
can sit forever in public avenues without stirring, and let it simmer and whisper through

02:14.100 --> 02:23.560
them like the Atesian winds, or as if inhaling ether, it only producing numbness and insensibility

02:23.560 --> 02:29.920
to pain, otherwise it would often be painful to bear, without affecting the consciousness.

02:30.700 --> 02:37.720
I hardly ever failed, when I rambled through the village, to see a row of such worthies,

02:37.960 --> 02:43.640
either sitting on a ladder sunning themselves with their bodies inclined forward and their

02:43.640 --> 02:49.860
eyes glancing along the line this way and that from time to time with a voluptuous expression,

02:50.640 --> 02:57.300
or else leaning against a barn with their hands in their pockets, like keratides, as

02:57.300 --> 03:03.100
if to prop it up, they, being commonly out of doors, heard whatever was in the wind.

03:04.780 --> 03:10.200
These are the coarsest mills in which all gossip is first rudely digested or cracked

03:10.200 --> 03:16.880
up before it is emptied into finer and more delicate hoppers with indoors. I observed

03:16.880 --> 03:23.740
that the vitals of the village were the grocery, the bar-room, the post-office, and the bank,

03:24.460 --> 03:30.900
and as a necessary part of the machinery they kept a bell, a big gun, and a fire-engine

03:30.900 --> 03:36.580
at convenient places, and the houses were so arranged as to make the most of mankind,

03:36.980 --> 03:43.360
in lanes and fronting one another so that every traveller had to run the gauntlet, and

03:43.360 --> 03:49.120
every man, woman, and child might get a lick at him. Of course those who were stationed

03:49.120 --> 03:54.780
nearest to the head of the line, where they could most see and be seen, and have the first

03:54.780 --> 04:00.780
blow at him, paid the highest prices for their places, and the few straggling inhabitants

04:00.780 --> 04:06.740
the outskirts, where long gaps in the line began to occur, and the traveller could get

04:06.740 --> 04:13.620
over walls or turn aside into cow-paths and so escape, paid a very slight ground or window

04:13.620 --> 04:21.140
tax. Signs were hung out on all sides to allure him, some to catch him by the appetite, as

04:21.140 --> 04:28.880
the tavern and victuling cellar, some by the fancy, as the dry goods-store and the jewellers,

04:29.280 --> 04:35.760
and others by the hair or the feet or the skirts, as the barber, the shoemaker, or

04:35.760 --> 04:41.440
the tailor. Besides, there was a still more terrible standing invitation to call at every

04:41.440 --> 04:47.560
one of these houses, and company expected about these times. For the most part I escaped

04:47.560 --> 04:52.800
wonderfully from these dangers, either by proceeding at once boldly and without deliberation

04:52.800 --> 04:59.400
the goal, as is recommended to those who run the gauntlet, or by keeping my thoughts on

04:59.400 --> 05:08.240
high things, like Orpheus, who, loudly singing the praises of the gods to his lyre, drowned

05:08.240 --> 05:16.020
the voices of the sirens and kept out of danger. Sometimes I bolted suddenly, and nobody could

05:16.020 --> 05:21.080
tell my whereabouts, for I did not stand much about gracefulness, and never hesitated at

05:21.080 --> 05:28.120
the gap in a fence. I was even accustomed to make an eruption into some houses, where

05:28.120 --> 05:34.420
I was well entertained, and after learning the kernels and very last sieveful of news,

05:35.160 --> 05:39.980
what had subsided, the prospects of war and peace, and whether the world was likely to

05:39.980 --> 05:46.460
hold together much longer, I was let out through the rear avenues, and so escaped to the woods

05:46.460 --> 05:53.320
again. It was very pleasant, when I stayed late in town, to launch myself into the night,

05:54.200 --> 06:00.740
especially if it was dark and tempestuous, and set sail for some bright village parlour

06:00.740 --> 06:07.660
or lecture room, with a bag of rye or Indian meal upon my shoulder, for my snug harbour

06:07.660 --> 06:14.840
in the woods, having made all tight, without and withdrawn under hatches with a merry crew

06:14.840 --> 06:21.240
of thoughts, leaving only my outer man at the helm, or even tying up the helm when it

06:21.240 --> 06:29.560
was plain sailing. I had many a genial thought by the cabin fire, as I sailed. I was never

06:29.560 --> 06:37.580
cast away, nor distressed in any weather, though I encountered some severe storms. It

06:37.580 --> 06:44.100
is darker in the woods, even in common nights, than most suppose. I frequently had to look

06:44.100 --> 06:49.480
up at the opening between the trees above the path in order to learn my route, and,

06:49.820 --> 06:55.360
where there was no cart path, to feel with my feet the faint track which I had worn,

06:55.960 --> 07:01.780
or steer by the known relation of particular trees which I felt with my hands, passing

07:01.780 --> 07:07.500
between two pines, for instance, not more than eighteen inches apart, in the midst of

07:07.500 --> 07:14.840
the woods, invariably, in the darkest night. Sometimes, after coming home thus late in

07:14.840 --> 07:21.040
a dark and muggy night, when my feet felt the path which my eyes could not see, dreaming

07:21.040 --> 07:27.060
and absent-minded all the way, until I was aroused by having to raise my hand to lift

07:27.060 --> 07:32.960
the latch, I have not been able to recall a single step of my walk, and I have thought

07:33.300 --> 07:39.300
that perhaps my body would find its way home if its master should forsake it, as the hand

07:39.300 --> 07:45.340
finds its way to the mouth without assistance. Several times, when a visitor chanced to stay

07:45.340 --> 07:51.340
into evening, and it proved a dark night, I was obliged to conduct him to the cart path

07:51.340 --> 07:57.120
in the rear of the house, and then point out to him the direction he was to pursue, and

07:57.120 --> 08:01.220
keeping which he was to be guided rather by his feet than his eyes.

08:02.400 --> 08:07.360
One very dark night I directed thus on their way two young men who had been fishing in

08:07.360 --> 08:12.980
the pond. They lived about a mile off through the woods, and were quite used to the route.

08:13.980 --> 08:19.540
A day or two after one of them told me that they wandered about the greater part of the

08:19.540 --> 08:25.200
night, close by their own premises, and did not get home till toward morning, by which

08:25.200 --> 08:30.220
there had been several heavy showers in the meanwhile, and the leaves were very wet, they

08:30.220 --> 08:35.860
were drenched to their skins. I have heard of many going astray even in the village streets,

08:36.020 --> 08:41.620
when the darkness was so thick that you could cut it with a knife, as the saying is. Some

08:41.620 --> 08:46.120
who live in the outskirts, having come to town a-shopping in their wagons, have been

08:46.120 --> 08:51.500
obliged to put up for the night, and gentlemen and ladies making a call have gone half a

08:51.500 --> 08:56.600
mile out of their way, feeling the sidewalk only with their feet, and not knowing when

08:56.600 --> 09:04.060
they turned. It is a surprising and memorable as well as valuable experience to be lost

09:04.060 --> 09:12.600
in the woods any time. Often in a snowstorm, even by day, one will come out upon a well-known

09:12.600 --> 09:18.000
road, and yet find it impossible to tell which way leads to the village, though he knows

09:18.000 --> 09:24.760
he has travelled it a thousand times, he cannot recognize a feature in it, but it is as strange

09:24.760 --> 09:31.560
to him as if it were a road in Siberia. By night, of course, the perplexity is infinitely

09:31.560 --> 09:37.840
greater. In our most trivial walks we are constantly, though unconsciously, steering

09:37.840 --> 09:44.000
like pilots by certain well-known beacons and headlands, and if we go beyond our usual

09:44.000 --> 09:49.060
course we still carry in our minds the bearing of some neighbouring cape, and not till we

09:49.060 --> 09:53.740
are completely lost or turned around, for a man needs only to be turned around once

09:53.740 --> 10:01.620
with his eyes shut in this world to be lost. Do we appreciate the vastness and strangeness

10:01.620 --> 10:10.880
of nature? Every man has to learn the points of compass again as often as beawakes, whether

10:10.880 --> 10:19.080
from sleep or any abstraction, not till we are lost. In other words, not till we have

10:19.080 --> 10:29.120
lost the world do we begin to find ourselves and realize where we are and the infinite

10:29.120 --> 10:36.660
extent of our relations. One afternoon near the end of the first summer, when I went to

10:36.660 --> 10:42.620
the village to get a shoe from the cobblers, I was seized and put into jail, because,

10:43.180 --> 10:50.120
as I have elsewhere related, I did not pay a tax to, or recognize the authority of, the

10:50.120 --> 10:55.860
state which buys and sells men, women, and children, like cattle, at the door of its

10:55.860 --> 11:03.820
senate house. I had gone down to the woods for other purposes, but wherever a man goes

11:03.820 --> 11:11.180
men will pursue and paw him with their dirty institutions, and if they can constrain him

11:11.180 --> 11:19.160
to belong to their desperate odd-fellow society. It is true, I might have resisted forcibly

11:19.160 --> 11:27.400
with more or less effect, might have run amok against society, but I preferred that society

11:27.400 --> 11:35.540
should run amok against me, it being the desperate party. However, I was released the next day,

11:36.100 --> 11:42.900
obtained my mended shoe, and returned to the woods, in season to get my dinner of huckleberries

11:42.900 --> 11:49.760
on Fairhaven Hill. I was never molested by any person but those who represented the state.

11:50.820 --> 11:57.220
I had no lock nor bolt but for the desk which held my papers, not even a nail to put over

11:57.220 --> 12:04.480
my latch or windows. I never fastened my door night or day, though I was to be absent several

12:04.480 --> 12:10.980
days, not even when the next fall I spent a fortnight in the woods of Maine. And yet

12:10.980 --> 12:18.360
my house was more respected than if it had been surrounded by a file of soldiers. The

12:18.360 --> 12:24.480
tired rambler could rest and warm himself by my fire, the literary amuse himself with

12:24.480 --> 12:31.120
a few books on my table, or the curious, by opening my closet door, see what was left

12:31.120 --> 12:37.600
of my dinner and what prospect I had of supper. Yet though many people of every class came

12:37.600 --> 12:43.520
this way to the pond, I suffered no serious inconvenience from these sources, and I never

12:43.520 --> 12:50.200
missed anything but one small book, a volume of Homer, which perhaps was improperly gilded,

12:50.500 --> 12:54.260
and this I trust a soldier of our camp has found by this time.

12:56.740 --> 13:02.900
I am convinced that if all men were to live as simply as I then did, thieving and robbery

13:02.900 --> 13:09.820
would be unknown. These take place only in communities where some have got more than

13:09.820 --> 13:18.160
is sufficient, while others have not enough. The pope's homers would soon get properly

13:18.160 --> 13:30.960
distributed. Nec bella feront faginus astabat dom scifus ante dapus. Nor wars did men molest

13:31.300 --> 13:39.500
when only beech and bowls were in request. You who govern public affairs, what need have

13:39.500 --> 13:48.100
you to employ punishments? Love virtue, and the people will be virtuous. The virtues of

13:48.100 --> 13:55.960
a superior man are like the wind. The virtues of a common man are like the grass. Eye the

13:55.960 --> 14:00.660
grass, when the wind passes over it, bends.

